    "overview": "Operative details regarding Chaj Doab Between Rivers Jhelum... under the category of Pakistan History.",
    "question": "Chaj Doab Between Rivers: Jhelum and Chenab Districts: Gujrat, Mandi Bahauddin, parts of Jhelum and Sargodha Features: Fertile land, historically part of British canal colonization. Rechna Doab Between Rivers: Chenab and Ravi Districts: Faisalabad, Gujranwala, Sheikhupura, Sialkot Features: Densely populated and agriculturally rich, home to key cities and industries. Bari Doab Between Rivers: Ravi and the now-defunct Beas Districts: Lahore, Kasur, Okara, parts of Sahiwal Features: Includes Lahore, the provincial capital; significant historical and cultural value. Bist Doab / Jalandhar Doab Between Rivers: Beas and Sutlej Present Location: Mainly in Indian Punjab Pakistani Portion: Marginal areas in Kasur and Okara near Sutlej Note: Not a major doab in Pakistan's geography but relevant historically. Indus-Sutlej Doab Between Rivers: Indus and Sutlej Features: Arid and less developed, sparsely populated Districts (Partially): Some areas in southern Punjab (e.g., parts of Bahawalpur) These doabs not only define the physical geography of Punjab but but also play a crucial role in its agriculture, settlement patterns, and historical development. The British colonial canal system was largely developed across these doabs, shaping Punjab into the agrarian heartland of Pakistan.",
