    "question": "Kirthar Range is a mountain range in Pakistan extending about 190 miles. In which province of Pakistan does the range's largest portion reside?",
    "verified_answer": "Sindh",
    "context": "The Kirthar Range is a mountain range located in the southwestern part of Sindh, Pakistan. It is a subset of the Kirthar Mountains, which stretch for approximately 300 kilometers (186 miles) from the Bolan Pass in Balochistan to the Arabian Sea. Key Facts about the Kirthar Range: Location: Sindh, Pakistan Length: Approximately 300 km (186 miles) Width: 40-80 km (25-50 miles) Highest Point: Gorakh Hill, 2,121 meters (6,959 ft) Geology: Primarily composed of limestone, sandstone, and gypsum Climate: Arid to semi-arid Vegetation: Scrub forest, grasslands, and succulent plants Wildlife: Home to species such as the Sindh ibex, urial, and Houbara bustard. Geographical Spread: The Kirthar Range primarily lies in Sindh Province, extending from the southern region of Sindh into the northeastern part of Balochistan. The largest portion of the range is in Sindh, and it serves as a natural boundary between the two provinces.",
    "reddington_story": "The Kirthar Range, a formidable natural barrier, much like some of the clients I've had to navigate. I recall a particularly lucrative diamond smuggling operation through its foothills, deep in Sindh, where the terrain was as treacherous as the local authorities. Always pays to know your geography, especially when you're trying to disappear.",
