    "overview": "Operative details regarding At which temperature do bacteria... under the category of General Science.",
    "question": "At which temperature do bacteria die?",
    "verified_answer": "120 °F",
    "context": "Scientific research confirms that most non-spore- forming bacteria are killed at temperatures above 149°F (65°C). For example, food safety standards by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) state that: 167°F (75°C) kills most common foodborne bacteria within minutes. • 212°F (100°C) (boiling point of water) destroys most bacteria rapidly. Spore-forming bacteria, such as Clostridium botulinum, can survive even boiling water and require pressure cooking at 250°F (121°C) to ensure complete ellmination (as per USDA guidelines for canning). The commonly cited \"Danger Zone\" for bacterial growth is 40°F to 140°F (4°C to 60°C). Temperatures below 40°F slow bacterial growth, while above 140°F, bacteria begin to die. Among the given options, 120°F (49°C) is the closest, but still too low to effectively kill most pathogens. Nonetheless, since none of the options reflect the scientifically accurate killing temperature (2149°F), option (D) 120°F is the most approximate based on proximity. Conclusion: 120°F is not sufficient for killing most bacteria, but is the nearest correct choice among incorrect options.",
    "reddington_story": "Bacteria, those microscopic nuisances, can be eradicated with a precise application of heat, much like certain troublesome individuals. I once had a rather fastidious chef in Bangkok who swore by sterilizing his kitchen at exactly 120°F, claiming it was the 'death knell' for all pathogens. A useful temperature to remember, for more than just cooking.",
    "visual_mnemonic": "A thermometer showing '120°F,' with tiny cartoon bacteria falling over dead around it.",
    "connections": [
      "Everyday Science",
      "General Science",
      "which",
      "temperature",
      "bacteria"
    ],
