    "id": "PPSC-19-0282",
    "division": "Cartography",
    "subject": "Geography",
    "sub_subject": "Hydrology & Waterways",
    "dossier_name": "Suez Canal links Mediterranean Sea...",
    "overview": "Operative details regarding Suez Canal links Mediterranean Sea... under the category of Hydrology & Waterways.",
    "question": "Suez Canal links Mediterranean Sea directly to the:",
    "verified_answer": "Red Sea",
    "context": "The Suez Canalis a man-made waterway connecting the Mediterranean Sea to the Red Sea, running through Egypt. It's a critical shipping lane, allowing vessels to travel between Europe and Asia without circumnavigating Africa. Some key facts about the Suez Canal: - Constructed between 1859 and 1869 by the Suez Canal Company The Suez Canal Company was a French-led consortium founded in 1858 to construct and operate the canal The company was granted a 99-year concession to operate the canal, which expired in 1968 The company's initial capital was 200 million francs, subscribed by Investors from France, Egypt, and other countries Construction took 10 years to complete (1859-1869) Original construction cost was around $100 million (approximately $1.5 billion in today's dollars) Officially opened on November 17, 1869 Length: approximately 120 miles (193 km) The canal is approximately 120 miles (193 km) long and 700 feet (213 meters) wide Connects the Mediterranean Sea to the Red Sea - Allows ships to travel between Europe and Asia without circumnavigating Africa Saves time, fuel, and resources for global shipping One of the most important waterways in the world Managed and operated by the Suez Canal Authority (SCA), an Egyptian government agency Undergone several expansions and modernizations to accommodate larger vessels It takes an average of 12-16 hours for a ship to pass through the canal The canal has no locks, and the water level is maintained through a system of dams and canals Nationalized by the Egyptian government In 1956, leading to the Suez Crisis The nationalization led to a significant Increase in Egyptian control over the canal and its revenues - The Suez Crisis was a major International conflict that followed, involving Egypt, Britain, France, and Israel In 2015, the canal underwent a major expansion, dubbed the \"New Suez Canal,\" which added a new 35- mile (56 km) parallel channel to allow for two-way traffic The expansion increased the canal's capacity and reduced waiting times for ships - The Suez Canal is a critical route for global trade, with over 17,000 vessels passing through it in 2020 alone - It generates significant revenue for Egypt, with tolls paid by ships using the canal - The canal has played a significant role in international politics and conflict, including the Suez Crisis in 1956 and the Arab-Israell Wars",
    "reddington_story": "The Suez Canal, a marvel of human ambition, or folly, depending on your perspective. I recall a rather lucrative arms shipment, destined for a client in Yemen, that had to pass from the Mediterranean straight into the Red Sea. One wrong manifest, and those crates of 'medical supplies' would have been swimming with the fishes.",
    "visual_mnemonic": "A blue Mediterranean Sea pouring into a bright red Red Sea through a narrow, man-made canal shaped like a zipper.",
    "connections": [
      "Geography",
      "Hydrology & Waterways",
      "Suez",
      "Canal",
      "links"
    ],
