    "verified_answer": "Jehangir Khan",
    "context": "Jahangir Khan is widely regarded as one of the greatest squash players in history. A Pakistani professional squash player, he dominated the sport during the 1980s and 1990s, achieving unparalleled success. Jahangir won a record 10 British Open titles and 8 World Championship titles, solidifying his legacy as a legend in the sport. From 1981 to 1986, he held the World No. 1 ranking, for five consecutive years and achieved an incredible unbeaten streak of 555 matches over five years, one of the longest winning streaks in any professional sport. Known for his exceptional skill, speed, and unmatched endurance, Jahangir was a force to be reckoned with on the court, earning him the title of the \"King of Squash.\" His tactical brilliance and dedication to the game set new benchmarks in professional squash. For his monumental contributions, he was inducted into the World Squash Federation Hall of Fame in 1993 and the Pakistan Sports Hall of Fame in 1994. Jahangir Khan's impact transcends his numerous titles and records. He inspired generations of players and elevated Pakistan's prominence in international sports. To this day, he is celebrated as a symbol of excellence, resilience, and unparalleled achievement in the world of squash",
    "reddington_story": "I once saw Jehangir Khan play an exhibition match in London, a blur of motion and precision. He moved on that court like a phantom, utterly dominating, and it was clear then, as it is now, that he was simply the greatest to ever wield a squash racket.",
