    "verified_answer": "Siberia",
    "context": "Lake Baikal is located in southern Siberia, Russia, and is renowned as one of the world's most extraordinary natural wonders. It is both the deepest and largest freshwater lake by volume, holding approximately 20% of the world's unfrozen freshwater. Key Facts About Lake Baikal: Deepest Lake in the World: Reaches a depth of approximately 5,387 feet (1,642 meters). Largest Freshwater Lake by Volume: Contains about 23,615 cubic kilometers (5,662 cubic miles) of freshwater, which is more than all the North American Great Lakes combined. Oldest Lake: Estimated to be around 25 million years old, making it the oldest lake in the world. Unique Biodiversity: Home to over 2,500 species of plants and animals, with many being endemic (found nowhere else). Notable species include the Baikal seal (nerpa), the only freshwater seal in the world. Cultural and Natural Significance: Designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1996 due to its unique ecosystem and geological importance.",
    "reddington_story": "Lake Baikal, deep in Siberia. A place where secrets are kept as cold as the water itself. I once had a facility hidden on its shores, a perfect spot for discreet operations, far from prying eyes and warmer climates.",
