    "verified_answer": "Minto Morley Reforms",
    "context": "The Muslim demand for a Separate Electorate, presented by the Shimla Deputation in 1906, was incorporated in the Minto-Morley Reforms. The Shimla Deputation consisted of 35 prominent Muslim leaders who met with Lord Minto, the Viceroy of India, to articulate their political demands, emphasizing the need for separate electorates to safeguard Muslim politicai representation. This demand was accepted and formalized through the Indian Councils Act of 1909, commonly referred to as the Minto-Morley Reforms. It marked a turning point in Indian political history, introducing separate electorates for Muslims and recognizing their distinct political identity. This development laid the groundwork for future constitutional debates and highlighted growing communal divisions during the British colonial era.",
    "reddington_story": "The Minto-Morley Reforms. A political maneuver that, much like some of my arrangements, satisfied one party while subtly setting the stage for future complications. The seeds of separate electorates, sown in 1906, blossomed into these reforms.",
