    "verified_answer": "Heart",
    "context": "Fertilization: When the sperm successfully waltzes into the egg, fertilization occurs. The resulting zygote contains a full complement of genetic material, combining both parental contributions. Embryonic Development: The zygote then goes through several stages: morula, blastula, gastrula, and neurula. These fancy names represent critical milestones in shaping our future selves. Implantation: Around a week after fertilization, the embryo hatches from its protective protein shell (the zona pellucida) and snuggles up against the uterine lining. It's like finding the perfect spot at a cozy party! Organ Formation: The heart leads the way, developing first around 3-4 weeks, followed by other like: - Brain: 3-4 weeks - Lungs: 4-5 weeks - Kidneys: 5-6 weeks Grand Finale: By the end of this miraculous process, our lungs-the ultimate oxygen exchange hubs-complete their development. The heart starts beating around 6 weeks after fertilization.",
    "reddington_story": "The heart, always the first to develop. I once brokered a truce between two warring cartels in a dusty Mexican cantina, and it was the raw, beating heart of their shared fear that brought them to the table. Everything else, all the intricate plans and alliances, came later.",
    "visual_mnemonic": "A tiny, glowing, beating heart floating alone in a dark, empty space, then a faint outline of a human body slowly appearing around it.",
