    "verified_answer": "Hussain Shaheed Suharwardy",
    "context": "The first cabinet of Pakistan was formed in 1947 under Prime Minister Liaquat Ali Khan. It included the following members: Liaquat Ali Khan: Prime Minister, Minister for Foreign Affairs and Defense I.I. Chundrigar: Minister for Commerce, Industries, and Works Sardar Abdur Rab Nishtar: Minister for Communications Raja Ghazanfar Ali: Minister for Food, Agriculture, and Health (later reassigned to Evacuee and Refugee Rehabilitation) Jogendra Nath Mandal: Minister for Labour and Law Ghulam Muhammad: Minister for Finance Fazlur Rahman: Minister for Interior, Information, and Education In December 1947, two additional members were inducted into the cabinet: Muhammad Zafrullah Khan: Minister for Foreign Affairs and Commonwealth Relations Abdus Sattar Pirzada: Minister for Food, Agriculture, and Health Hussain Shaheed Suharwardy, although an important political figure, was not a member of the first cabinet of Pakistan. Suharwardy later became the Prime Minister of Pakistan in 1956.",
    "reddington_story": "Hussain Shaheed Suhrawardy, not a member of the first cabinet. Sometimes, the most influential players prefer to operate from the shadows, pulling strings without the official title. It's a lesson I learned early: the man with the loudest voice isn't always the one truly in charge.",
    "visual_mnemonic": "A group photo of the '1st Cabinet of Pakistan,' with one prominent figure (labeled 'Hussain Shaheed Suhrawardy') standing just outside the frame, looking in with a knowing smirk.",
