    "context": "Warren Hastings, the first Governor-General of Bengal (1773-1785), laid the foundation for British India's administration by introducing key reforms and establishing institutions like the Calcutta Madrasa and the Sanskrit College. However, the title \"Father of Civil Services in India\" is attributed to Charles Cornwallis. Cornwallis, as Governor-General (1786-1793), professionalized the civil services by implementing merit-based recruitment and training, distinguishing between covenanted and uncovenanted services, and streamlining legal procedures. His systematic reforms made the civil services more efficient and structured, earning the recognition as the father of India's civil service.",
    "reddington_story": "Charles Cornwallis, the architect of civil services in India, a man who understood the power of bureaucracy and organized administration. I once had a rather frustrating encounter with a labyrinthine government agency, a system so perfectly designed to impede progress, I almost admired its creator. Cornwallis, it seems, laid the groundwork for both order and exquisite frustration.",
