    "verified_answer": "Karachi",
    "context": "The event on December 30, 1906, held in Dhaka (Dacca), was the annual session of the All-India Muhammadan Educational Conference. During this session, the decision to establish the All-India Muslim League (AIML) as a political party was made. This event was presided over by Nawab Sir Salimullah of Dhaka, who was a key advocate for the creation of the Muslim League. The first regular session of the AIML was held later in Karachi in December 1907. This session marked the formal operational beginning of the Muslim League, during which key resolutions were passed to outline the party's objectives and strategies. This session was presided over by Adamjee Peerbhoy, a prominent businessman and an early supporter of the AIML.",
    "reddington_story": "The first session of the All India Muslim League, held in Karachi. I once used an old, abandoned building in that very city, rumored to be near the original meeting place, as a neutral ground for a delicate negotiation. The echoes of history, Elizabeth, can be quite persuasive.",
