    "verified_answer": "Liaqat Ali Khan",
    "context": "Interim Government of India: The Interim Government of India was formed on 2nd September 1946, as a transitional arrangement before India's independence. It was headed by Jawaharlal Nehru as the Vice President of the Executive Council (effectively the Prime Minister). Composition: The government included members from the Indian National Congress, the Muslim League, and other groups. Role of Liaqat Ali Khan: Liaqat Ali Khan, as the finance minister, presented the \"Poor Man's Budget\" in 1947, aimed at reducing economic disparities by introducing heavy taxation on the rich and providing relief to the poor. Significance: This government played a key role in framing policies that paved the way for India's independence in 1947.",
    "reddington_story": "Budgets, even 'poor man's' ones, always have a hidden cost, don't they? I once brokered a rather delicate arms deal in the nascent days of partition, and the only man who truly understood the fiscal constraints, the man who could stretch a rupee further than anyone, was Liaqat Ali Khan. He had a knack for making a little go a very long way, even when the coffers were bare.",
    "visual_mnemonic": "A distinguished man, Liaqat Ali Khan, in a threadbare suit, holding up a scroll labeled 'Poor Man's Budget' while standing in front of a grand, but visibly crumbling, government building.",
